    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-10-16T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-10-16T04:00:00-05:00" n="778"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d778">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.515/10–1644: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-16T12:00:00+03:00"
                            >October 16, 1944—noon.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 16—7:03 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3944. ReDept’s 2427, October 13, 8 p.m. On September 11 as indicated in my 3440,
                    September 12, 4 p.m.,<note n="5" xml:id="d778fn5">Not printed.</note> I informed
                    Molotov in a letter that American troops would be paid in Allied military marks
                    at the rate of 10 marks to the dollar and that this was not a general rate of
                    exchange and would not be announced publicly.</p>
                <p>The British Embassy sent a similar communication on September 22.</p>
                <p>On October 4 our radio bulletin contained an item to the effect that a joint
                    announcement had been made by the War and Treasury Departments to the effect
                    that an Allied military mark had been distributed to troops invading Germany on
                    a provisional basis of 10 marks to the dollar. In view of these circumstances I
                    do not think that it would be advisable for us to make any further communication
                    to the Soviet Government at this time on this subject.</p>
                <p>Molotov has not replied to my letter referred to above, and I have no information
                    as to the policy the Soviet authorities intend to follow in this respect.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
